German Credit Report

Business Insights based on Charts

Based on these two charts, customers which have higher amounts tend to be labeled as bad customers, but those with the lower amounts tend to be labeled as good.

If the customer has fewer dependents, they are more likely to be a good customer.

train_index <- sample(1:nrow(my_germ), size=0.8*nrow(my_germ))


germ_train <- my_germ[train_index,]
germ_test <- my_germ[-train_index,]

my_logit <- glm(binary~checking+duration+age+telephon+amount+savings+
                  installp+coapp, data=germ_train, family="binomial")

summary(my_logit)

Business Insights based on logistic coefficients

for every additional unit of checking, the offs of business success increase by r 100*(exp(my_summary$coefficients[2])-1)%

for every additional month of duration, the odds of business success change by r 100*(exp(my_summary$coefficients[3])-1)%

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.
